Introduction

This project aims to analyze water potability using various machine learning techniques applied to a specific dataset. We set up several models to evaluate the prediction capacity of each method and compare their performances. Well see several supervised classification techniques by training set model, tree, random forrest logit model and tree nnet models

Library

We installed several library to perform our different test and models

1. Dataset

We download the dataset from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nayanack/water-probability/data

The data provides information about whether the water is potable or not, based on various water characteristics variables.

There is 9 explicative variables and the 10th variable is whether the is potable or not:

pH: pH of the water (measured in pH units).

Hardness: Hardness of the water (measured in mg/L).

Solids: Total dissolved solids in the water (measured in ppm).

Chloramines: Amount of chloramines in the water (measured in ppm).

Sulfate: Amount of sulfate in the water (measured in mg/L).

Conductivity: Conductivity of the water (measured in S/cm).

Organic_carbon: Amount of organic carbon in the water (measured in ppm).

Trihalomethanes: Amount of trihalomethanes in the water (measured in g/L).

Turbidity: Turbidity of the water (measured in NTU).

Potability: Potability of the water (1 indicates potable, 0 indicates non-potable).

Summary Statistics:

The dataset contains 3276 entries. The columns pH, Sulfate, and Trihalomethanes have missing values. The data types of the columns are float64 for features and int64 for the target variable (Potability).

3 Tree

The use of a decision tree in our project serves to better understand the data, identifying important variables

tree <- rpart(Potability~.,data=training, method = "class")
prp(tree,extra=1,faclen=5, box.col=c("red","green")[tree$frame$yval])

This tree give us a lot of informations. In fact we can see our model follow specific conditions: 1st condition depending on sulfate: if sulfate <259 the water is prdicted not patable with 49 who are really not patable and 17 who are potable so with wrong prediction. If sulfate >= 259 then we go to next condition who is Sulfate <409. And we follow the tree to know if the water potability prdiction dtermined by the tree structure Based on the distribution of the tree we can think Sulfate is the variable who is the most importante.

To verify this supposition we check forvariables importance on the tree

tree$variable.importance

barplot(tree$variable.importance, horiz = TRUE, col = "purple")

This graph give the importance of each variable. We can see the most importante is Sulfate like our assumption. We also can see Sulfate importance =37 and if we add all the other variables importance we are near to 37 so we can said Sulfate determine for a very big part of our model like approximately 50% of the model. We can also see on the graph Turdibity for example as a very small impact on our model and we we could expect this because the variable is not even in the tree

This graph is the comparison between the variable ph and Sulfate because they are the most impactful variable to determine if the water is potable or not

4 Random Forest

The random forest algorithm creates multiple decision trees using different subsets of the data and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and prevent overfitting. It highlights the most important variables contributing to the models predictions by assessing their impact across all trees.

For this method, we train it on training, then we predict thanks to this training on testing and we compare.

training_complete <- na.omit(training)
randomf1 <- randomForest(as.factor(training_complete$Potability) ~ ., data = training_complete)
randomf1_pred <- predict(randomf1, testing, type="response")

importance(randomf1)

5. Logit Model

8. Conclusion and limits

In summary, our study aimed to predict water potability using various machine learning models. We explored decision trees, random forests, logistic regression, and TreeNet models, identifying sulfate and pH as significant predictors.

Some models, like logistic regression and TreeNet, showed poor performance, indicating potential issues with model choice or parameter settings. Further tuning and optimization are required. The study did not explore advanced feature machine learning techniques that could potentially improve the models predictive power. The datasets size and the presence of missing or noisy data may have impacted the accuracy and generalizability of our models. Also, our study did not explicitly address the presence of outliers in the dataset. Outliers can skew the results and affect the accuracy of the models, potentially leading to biased predictions. Detecting and appropriately handling outliers could improve the robustness and reliability of our models.
